based as well. I live in New England and I have yet to encounter anybody that has redshirted their children for sports, age or size. I am not saying it doesn't happen, but it certainly doesn't happen often and isn't an acceptable reason around here to redshirt. &#10;Redshirting is common in my community/school district. In most cases it isn't done for size or age advantages. Parents do it to ensure their children are on a level playing field academically, emotionally and socially. In general, redshirted children do not continue on in preschool. They move on to what in our area is referred to as a 5+ program where they work at an appropriate academic level but also work or social and emotional behaviors that are necessary for success in kindergarten. &#10;I will say, I don't know if I buy into the studies that say redshirting is detrimental. As I said, redshirting is common here. We have some of the highest testing scores and on to college rates in the country. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1270" language="en" documentId="5205" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="MandarinOranges" date="04/05/2012" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a32503567/yet_another_redshirting_debate?cpg=17" topic="redshirting" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="5205" notes="" title="Yet another redshirting debate"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="163"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="164" end="565"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="566" end="1059"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="1060" end="1270"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>